      "solution": "g = input().strip()\nparts = input().split()\n\nA = int(parts[0])\nB = int(parts[1]) if len(parts) > 1 else 0\n\nif g == \"BUFFER\":\n    print(A)\nelif g == \"NOT\":\n    print(1 - A)\nelif g == \"AND\":\n    print(A & B)\nelif g == \"OR\":\n    print(A | B)\nelif g == \"NAND\":\n    print(1 - (A & B))\nelif g == \"NOR\":\n    print(1 - (A | B))\nelif g == \"XOR\":\n    print(A ^ B)\nelif g == \"XNOR\":\n    print(1 - (A ^ B))",
      "statement": "This is <<Chapter 1>> of the <<Digital Logic Basics>> series.\nIn this chapter, you will evaluate the output of a single logic gate given its binary input value(s).\nA logic gate takes one or two binary inputs ({{0}} or {{1}}) and produces a binary output according to a well‑defined rule.\nThe supported gates in this puzzle are:\n{{BUFFER}}, {{NOT}}, {{AND}}, {{OR}}, {{NAND}}, {{NOR}}, {{XOR}}, {{XNOR}}",
